args: ...Wait. You want Elias to be my assistant?
He needs different experiences while he's\nhere, and you have the most varied work\nschedule of anyone in the castle.
Well, I suppose I could always use an\nextra set of hands.

However! This work will not be easy;
no assistant of mine will be permitted
to slack or goldbrick to any degree.
Is that clear?
And you'd best hurry—the sun won't\naccomodate any dallying.
Elias! I want you to scrub all the exposed\ngrout in the entire castle!
Urk! I mean, o-of course, ma'am!
Whew! Cleo's working me to the bone.\nI can't believe how many different kinds\nof tasks I've had to do so far.
Still, I wonder how this is supposed to\nhelp with my singing?
There you are, Elias. I'm starting dinner,\nso I'll need you to assist me.
Please dice these onions finely.\n...Yes, that's it. Good.
When you're done, you can drop them\ninto these two pots.
Er, ma'am? Why are there TWO pots?
We're only making one thing, right?
This is so we can adjust the seasoning.
Different people have different palates.\nRanzal, for example, enjoys rich flavors,\nwhile Elisanne prefers a lighter touch.
This way people have an option.
Don't you think it's selfish of people to\nexpect you to cater to them?
No one asked me to do this, Elias.\nI took it upon myself.
But you're an amazing chef, Cleo.\nANYTHING you make will be good.
Don't you get tired of taking all these extra\nsteps? I mean, you already do practically\neverything around here.
Is that a touch of concern I sense?\nHow kind of you.
I know it might seem like I'm going out of\nmy way to increase my workload.
However, if that extra work leads to people\nenjoying my food more, it's no trouble.
Think of it this way: You could simply\neat bread for the rest of your life and\nstay alive, yes?
But eating is more than just staying\nalive; it's a cultural bonding experience,\nespecially in a company like ours.
So even if it's more work for me to tailor\nfood to specific tastes, it's all right\nbecause everyone benefits in the end.
Of course, it would be easier to simply let\nthe recipe do all the work for me.
But since I'm already going to the trouble\nof cooking, I'd rather people truly enjoy it.
I guess I never thought of it like that.
I imagine it's much the same for you.\nYou want people to connect with your\nmusic and not just listen to it, yes?
Every time I get on stage, I hope to sing\nsomething that resonates with people.

...Except now that I'm thinking about it,
all I've been doing is reading sheet music.
I've essentially just been following a
musical recipe.
Following a recipe isn't an entirely\nbad thing.
But if a person doesn't like the recipe\nyou're starting with, none of your hard\nwork is going to matter.
Well, that's more than enough chatter,\nI would think. We've work to do.
This grub's even better than usual, Cleo!
Agreed. It amazes me how you're able to\nuse such a delicate hand with the flavors.
Actually, Elias was a big help today.
You're quite the talented young man,\naren't you? Many thanks for your work.
We're both just happy you like it.
C'mon, Cleo. You did all the work here;\nI was just a glorified knife boy.
When people thank you, you should be\ngracious and accept their kindness.
Now then! Do you see how much everyone\nis enjoying the food we made?
Sure. I mean, Ranzal's already going back\nfor thirds.
Cooking doesn't stop when you finish\nmaking the food.
The work continues until you are certain\nthat the feelings you put into your creation\nhave been received.
Hmm. I imagine that's something else I\ncan apply to my singing.
All I've been focusing on is singing as\nskillfully as possible—I haven't thought\nabout the people listening to me at all.
You're incredible, Cleo! If you ever need\nany more help, just let me know.
I think you have more to teach me about\nhow to get my feelings across to people.
I will be happy to help.
